138

00:09:09,950  -->  00:09:12,310
This is particularly useful when you need to

139

00:09:12,310  -->  00:09:15,470
iterate over a range that doesn't start at zero.

140

00:09:15,470  -->  00:09:19,190
You can specify a start and end point for

141

00:09:19,190  -->  00:09:20,870
the range function so that there is

142

00:09:20,870  -->  00:09:24,035
a specific point in which each function will execute and stop.

143

00:09:24,035  -->  00:09:25,810
Let's see an example of this.

144

00:09:25,810  -->  00:09:28,880
We'll write a for loop and we'll say for i

145

00:09:28,880  -->  00:09:38,360
range (2,7): we'll say print(i).

146

00:09:38,360  -->  00:09:44,880
In this example, we specify that we want the range to start at two and end at seven.

147

00:09:44,880  -->  00:09:49,410
This means that our for loop will print numbers 2-6,

148

00:09:49,410  -->  00:09:52,845
which is one less than the end point specified.

149

00:09:52,845  -->  00:09:54,990
This allows you to control

150

00:09:54,990  -->  00:09:59,780
both the starting and stopping points of your loop making the code more flexible.

151

00:09:59,780  -->  00:10:03,430
Let's see what happens when we execute this code.

152

00:10:04,190  -->  00:10:09,990
When we run this code, we'll see 2,3,4,5,6,

153

00:10:09,990  -->  00:10:12,210
and then once it gets to seven, it will stop.

154

00:10:12,210  -->  00:10:15,670
That's why it only prints these numbers here.

155

00:10:16,860  -->  00:10:22,160
Finally, the range function allows us to introduce a step argument,

156

00:10:22,160  -->  00:10:25,260
which specifies the increment between numbers.

157

00:10:25,260  -->  00:10:28,780
This is useful when you need to skip numbers in your sequence.

158

00:10:28,780  -->  00:10:31,500
Think of this like a skipper that allows you to

159

00:10:31,500  -->  00:10:34,800
pass over numbers in the range with a pattern.

160

00:10:34,800  -->  00:10:41,520
For example, we want to iterate over every second number or every other number.

161

00:10:41,520  -->  00:10:45,510
How would we do that? Let's see how to do that.

162

00:10:45,510  -->  00:10:52,590
First, we'll define a for loop and we'll say for i in range and we'll

163

00:10:52,590  -->  00:11:02,050
put 0,10,2: then we'll print (i) to print out each item.

164

00:11:02,050  -->  00:11:04,290
Can you guess what's happening here?

165

00:11:04,290  -->  00:11:08,450
This is going to print every second number from zero,

166

00:11:08,450  -->  00:11:10,810
the start to 10,

167

00:11:10,810  -->  00:11:13,270
the stop with two being

168

00:11:13,270  -->  00:11:19,530
this skipper element that we define for our range function like this.

169

00:11:19,530  -->  00:11:22,250
When we execute the code, we'll see this.

170

00:11:22,880  -->  00:11:32,370
See 0,2,4,6,8, and then once it gets to 10,

171

00:11:32,370  -->  00:11:34,895
it stops and doesn't execute beyond that.

172

00:11:34,895  -->  00:11:37,410
That's why we see these numbers here.

173

00:11:37,410  -->  00:11:39,570
We're telling Python to count

174

00:11:39,570  -->  00:11:43,970
every other number by setting the step argument here to two.

175

00:11:43,970  -->  00:11:48,310
To break it down, 0 is our start number.

176

00:11:48,310  -->  00:11:54,805
It's an optional parameter we can pass in and defaults to 0, if not specified.

177

00:11:54,805  -->  00:11:59,210
The 10 is the end number, not optional,

178

00:11:59,210  -->  00:12:01,330
and the loop runs up to,

179

00:12:01,330  -->  00:12:03,230
but does not include this number,

180

00:12:03,230  -->  00:12:06,830
which is why we always have to pass in a number into range.

181

00:12:06,980  -->  00:12:10,340
Then 2 is the step number,

182

00:12:10,340  -->  00:12:15,020
which is also optional and defaults to one, if not specified.

183

00:12:15,020  -->  00:12:18,735
If the step argument was set to 3,

184

00:12:18,735  -->  00:12:22,335
instead of 2, Python will count every third number.

185

00:12:22,335  -->  00:12:25,040
Let's take a look at this example.

186

00:12:25,040  -->  00:12:29,120
If we were to copy this code, paste it in here,

187

00:12:29,120  -->  00:12:32,790
and then change 2 to 3,

188

00:12:33,860  -->  00:12:38,540
this will now output something a little different from what we saw earlier.

189

00:12:39,020  -->  00:12:44,260
By counting by three, we now see four numbers instead of five,

190

00:12:44,260  -->  00:12:46,780
